  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identity\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Assessing money laundering risks\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting\n- Identifying and reporting suspicious transactions\n- Filing Currency Transaction Reports\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\n3. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Training employees\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n5. Know Your Customer (KYC) Requirements\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Monitoring ongoing customer activities\n- Performing background checks\n\n6. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following guidelines from agencies like FinCEN\n- Adhering to international standards\n- Implementing risk-based compliance approaches\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminal financial activities and help detect potential illegal transactions. Non-compliance can result in significant legal and financial penalties.",
